         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0081">
               <p>Ann was born in <placeName>Newcastle</placeName>, the daughter of
                     <persName>William</persName> and <persName>Mary (Ellis) Avison</persName>, and
                  niece of <persName>Charles Avison</persName> (<date from="1710" to="1770"
                     >1710–1770</date>), the famous organist. <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> began corresponding with her
                  regularly in the mid 1760s, up to the point that she married <persName>Richard
                     Terry</persName> (<date from="1737" to="1804">1737–1804</date>) of
                     <placeName>Hull</placeName> in <date when="1767-11">Nov. 1767</date>. Only one
                  letter survives addressed to Mrs. Terry. See Roz Southey et al., <hi rend="italic"
                     >The Ingenious Mr. Avison</hi> (Newcastle: Tyne Bridge, <date when="2009"
                     >2009</date>), 53, 113–14.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
